				<h3>Should Diabetics avoid sugar altogether? </h3>
								
				<p>People often wonder if diabetics should avoid all kinds of sugar, all together. Of course, diabetics need to monitor their diet like a hawk. But incorporating occasional sweet treats into your diet can be okay. However, the amount of sugar a person with diabetes can consume depends on the following factors:</p>
				
				<ul>
					<li>Their activity levels. </li>
					
					<li>Are they trying to lose or maintain a healthy weight?</li>
					
					<li>Do they aspire to lower their blood glucose levels?</li>
				</ul>
				
				<p>The best way to set personal goals for proper nutrition and a well-balanced diet is by contacting a doctor or dietician. This is where LifeHeal comes to your rescue. Our certified dieticians specially curate plans for you by keeping your personal preferences in mind. 

</p>
				<img src="<?php echo $this->getSkinUrl('images/glucose-meter.jpg') ?>" style="width:100%;"/>
				
			<p>Additionally, according to organizations like American Diabetes Association, diabetics can eat occasional treats like chocolate, sweets, and other sugary foods, as long as they eat a well-balanced diet and do some form of physical activity. </p><ul><li>Have limited saturated fat.</li>
<li>Contain a modest amount of salt and sugar.</li>
<li>Contain plentiful protein, non-starchy vegetables, whole grains, fruits, and healthy fats like avocado. 
	</li></ul>
				
				
				
				<p>
Diabetics should have a sparse amount of sugar and be extra cautious about food labels. Foods claiming to be "sugar-free" or have "no added sugar" should be avoided. These usually contain calories and carbohydrates that can impact your blood sugar levels. Foods containing these sugar substitutes can also alter a person's sense of taste. </p>

<p>Common added sugars that are found in regular food items and people with diabetes should avoid are:</p>
<ul><li>Table sugar </li>
				<li>High fructose corn syrup</li>
				<li>Brown rice syrup</li>
				<li>Agave nectar </li>
				<li>Maple syrup</li>
				<li>Glucose</li>
				<li>Beet sugar</li>
				<li>Honey </li>
				</ul>

